quran[7]{c,v,t}:
  11,1,"Alif Lām Ra. A Scripture whose signs{1}were perfected, then detailed, from One Who is All-Wise, All-Aware:",footnotes:1:The Arabic word used is <i>ayat </i>(singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah </i>means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.
  11,2,"that youpl shall worship none but Allah.(Say) , “Indeed, I am to you from Him a warner and a herald of glad tidings."
  11,3,"So ask<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>your Lord for forgiveness then repent to Him, that He may grant you good enjoyment for a stated term and bestow His grace upon every graceful one. But if <span class=",footnotes:1:A grammatical shift from 2<sup>nd</sup> person to 3 person to 3<sup>rd</sup> person. person.,footnotes:2:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Al-Bazzi read it as: “But if you<sup>pl</sup> turn away,” turn away,”</span>
  11,4,"To Allah is your return, and He is All-Powerful over everything.”"
  11,5,"Undoubtedly, they do bend their chests to hide from Him. Undoubtedly, even as they cover themselves with their clothes, He knows whatever they keep secret and whatever they make public; He is indeed All-Knowing of what lies within the chests."